        <h1 class="about-title">How to Use this Site</h1>
        <div class="about-body">
          <div>

            <p>Welcome to the Macro Explain-o-matic!  Not sure what
            your macro does?  Trying to debug a macro that won't work?
            Help is just a few clicks away.</p>

            <h3>Step 1: Enter your WoW macro.</h3>

            <p>Paste or your write your macro in the text box and
            click "Explain this Macro!"</p>

            <p>If you are completely new to macros, please check out
            the <a href="/links">Macro Resources</a> section for
            several comprehensive WoW macro lists.  Any of them can be
            put in into the Explain-o-matic for an explanation of what
            it does.</p>

            <h3>Step 2: Reading the Macro Explanation.</h3>

            <p>The Explain-o-matic will give you a line-by-line
            English explanation of what your macro does.  When you
            mouse over a part of your macro, the English explanation
            of what it does will highlight also.</p>

            <p>Macro parameters recognized by the Explain-o-matic will
            look <font class="wowhead">like this</font>.  Mouse over
            these tokens to retrieve information from <a
            href="http://wowhead.com">Wowhead.com</a>.</p>

            <p>If the Explain-o-matic detects an issue with your
            macro, you will see the following symbol in your macro code:
            
            <p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font class="token">macro warning</font><sup class="warn">?</sup></p>

            <p>If the Explain-o-matic doesn't understand your macro
            (or detects a serious error), you will see the following
            symbol in your macro code:</p>

            <p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font class="token_error">macro error</font><sup class="error">!</sup></p>

            <p>Mouse over these for more information about macro
            problems.<p>

            You can turn macro warnings off any time by clicking:</p>

            <p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<code>Turn Warnings <input class="button" type="button"
            value="OFF"></input></code>

            <p>You can review a short version of this help section at
            any time by mousing over the help button in the right
            corner of the macro explanation:</p>

            <p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<input class="button" type="button"
            value="Help"></input></p>

            <h3>Step 3: Sharing Your Macro (and Explanation!)</h3>

            <p>The Explain-o-matic makes it easy to quickly save your
            macros and send them to your friends.  You'll never have
            to explain a macro to anyone again!</p>

            <p>Saving your macro takes a few quick steps.  First,
            select which classes can use your macro from the list of
            icons.  Click an icon to select that class.</p>

            <p>Next, add a few tags describing your macro.  What is
            useful for?  Click the tags underneath the next box to
            quickly add some of the example tags, or add your own.</p>

            <p>If you want, add some optional information to this
            macro.  Give it a title, author, or add some notes for
            other folks to use.</p>

            <p>That's it.  Click "Save" and you're done--your macro and
            its explanation are now saved, and can be viewed by
            anyone.</p>

          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

